---
description: Enforce Rails 8 WBEZ Bootstrap styling
globs: [
  "app/views/**/*",
  "app/helpers/**/*",
  "app/controllers/**/*",
  "app/assets/**/*",
  "config/**/*",
  "docs/design-system/**/*"
]
alwaysApply: true
---

This project uses Rails 8, Hotwire/Turbo, Bootstrap, and WBEZ-inspired editorial patterns.

Requirements:
- Always use Rails-native patterns.
- Always preserve Turbo and Hotwire compatibility.
- Prefer ERB partials, helpers, and Stimulus over custom JS frameworks.
- Prefer Bootstrap components wherever possible.
- Follow WBEZ design rules from `docs/design-system/bootstrap-wbez.md`.
- Reuse shared UI partials in `app/views/shared/ui` before creating new markup patterns.

Do:
- Use Bootstrap for navbar, offcanvas, buttons, cards, alerts, badges, forms, tabs, pagination, tables, and grid layout.
- Use Source Sans Pro for UI.
- Use Charter for editorial headlines and pull quotes.
- Use neutral surfaces and WBEZ red for primary actions.
- Keep layouts restrained, content-first, and high-contrast.
- Use `.prose-wbez` for article bodies.
- Use Turbo Frames for in-page result switching and pagination.

Do not:
- Introduce Tailwind, daisyUI, or React-style component patterns unless explicitly requested.
- Hardcode lots of inline styles in ERB.
- Invent new design tokens in views.
- Replace standard Rails form/link behavior with unnecessary JavaScript.
- Use playful gradients, glassmorphism, or over-decorated components.

- Use `/demo/logos` to inspect available downloaded brand assets before inventing logo treatments.
